From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Thu, 25 Jun 2026 09:33:43 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] brush: snoop self-shadowed /bin/sh scripts in-process (no
 fork+reexec)
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

In a -b box, /bin/sh (and the bash/dash aliases) are bind-shadowed with the
engine binary, so every nested `sh -c` / `sh script` / `#!/bin/sh` a build
spawns used to fork+reexec sarun and re-enter brush — the "sh storm" visible
during ./configure. This adds an in-process snoop: when a box brush shell is
about to fork an external command that resolves to our OWN binary, interpret
the script in-process on a clone of the calling shell instead.

Mechanism:
- brush-core: a thin embedder seam. A new `commands::ExecInterposer<SE>` trait
  with a cheap sync `wants(&Path)` filter (runs on every external exec, before
  any clone) and an async `run(sub, resolved, argv, params)`; an optional
  `Arc<dyn ExecInterposer>` field on Shell, inherited by clones, consulted at
  SimpleCommand::execute's external-exec point. `run` takes an owned subshell
  clone (so its future is 'static) and the caller's params (so per-command
  redirects/fds carry through), mirroring builtin_exec::run_one.
- sarun (brush.rs): SnoopInterposer implements the trait. Self-detection is
  box-side and config-free: the FUSE shadow keeps the path's own inode but
  serves the engine binary's size+content, so we compare a candidate's size +
  head bytes against /proc/self/exe (the musl-static stripped binary has no
  build-id). It parses the invocation conservatively (sh/dash only — bash and
  anything with options we don't model fall through to the fork path, which
  already builds a correct-mode shell on reentry), sets a unique synthetic
  $$/BASHPID, and runs the script through run_nested_pipelines — the SAME
  record-then-run loop the forked shim uses, so nested brush_prov rows are
  preserved. find/xargs -exec are covered (they dispatch via run_argv).

$$/BASHPID: Shell.synthetic_pid lets a snooped script report a distinct pid
(expansion.rs + set_snoop_identity), so concurrent in-process scripts get
unique conftest$$ temp files despite sharing one OS process.

test_brush_nested_sh_rs.py passes, now exercising the snoop path (case3's
error is tagged "(snooped)"); nested prov rows (case1/2), sh-vs-bash mode
(case9), and the `sh -c -- CMD` terminator (case10) all preserved.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
